# WASMnism: ClipClap Edge Gateway Benchmark

You are building a portable "ClipClap Edge Gateway" deployed across multiple WASM-first edge platforms (Akamai/Spin, Fastly, Cloudflare Workers) and AWS Lambda, producing a decision-grade price-per-performance scorecard for a future blog post.

## Hard Requirements

- Split architecture: Edge Gateway (WASM-deployable) + Inference Service (existing FastAPI).
- Gateway must return identical JSON schema across all platforms for the same inputs.
- Benchmark runs must be repeatable (N runs, report median).
- Security is job zero: never commit API keys, secrets, passwords, IP addresses, or credentials.
- Use .example templates for any config containing environment-specific values.

## Context Rules

- Read docs/PROJECT_STATE.local.md if it exists; otherwise docs/PROJECT_STATE.public.md.
- Read docs/OPERATIONS.local.md if it exists; otherwise docs/OPERATIONS.public.md.
- PROJECT_STATE and OPERATIONS files are private—never commit them.
- Never ask the user to paste tokens, kubeconfigs, API keys, or credentials into chat.

## Security Rules

- Never hardcode: API keys, secret keys, passwords, IP addresses, account IDs, or inference service URLs.
- Use environment variables or secret managers for all sensitive config.
- Provide .env.example and cost-config.example.yaml with placeholders only.
- Do not log secrets, credentials, or PII.
- Benchmark result JSON may contain IPs—keep raw results out of git (use .gitignore).

## Target Platforms

- Tier 1 (edge): Akamai Functions (Spin), Fastly Compute, Cloudflare Workers
- Tier 2 (baseline): AWS Lambda (regional)

## Deliverables

1. benchmark_contract.md: request/response schemas, SLO, fairness rules
2. edge-gateway/: core logic + platform adapters (spin, fastly, workers, lambda)
3. deploy/: scaffolding for each platform (make deploy-<target>)
4. bench/: k6 scripts, multi-region notes, results → scorecard
5. cost/: cost per 1M requests at SLO

## Blog Post Alignment

This project will produce a blog post similar to Anchoring GenAI (rag-ray-haystack). Structure: executive summary, narrative hook, disclosure, architecture, measurement contract, benchmark results, reproduce instructions. Use median of 7 runs; client-side timing as source of truth.
